[## [SECTION: Step 10 — Kubecost (Components #179–181)]]


10
04:26:54,000 --> 04:27:00,000
Now let's install Kubecost for cost visibility.
Kubecost tells you how much your Kubernetes cluster costs, down to the pod level.

11
04:27:00,000 --> 04:27:06,000
First, add the Kubecost Helm repository.
helm repo add kubecost https://kubecost.github.io/cost-analyzer/

12
04:27:06,000 --> 04:27:12,000
Install Kubecost in the monitoring namespace.
helm upgrade dash dash install kubecost kubecost/cost-analyzer dash dash namespace monitoring

13
04:27:12,000 --> 04:27:18,000
Set kubecostToken to your token.
Set prometheus.enabled to false and prometheus.fqdn to the kube-prometheus-stack Prometheus.

14
04:27:18,000 --> 04:27:24,000
Now create the cost allocation config.
We'll put it in infrastructure/kubecost/kubecost-cost-allocation.yaml

15
04:27:24,000 --> 04:27:30,000
The labelConfig splits cost by component using app.kubernetes.io/component.
And by environment using the environment label.

16
04:27:30,000 --> 04:27:36,000
shareTenancyCosts is set to true.
sharedNamespaces include monitoring, kube-system, and vault.

17
04:27:36,000 --> 04:27:42,000
This shares the cost of monitoring and system components across all tenants.
Apply the config with kubectl apply.

18
04:27:42,000 --> 04:27:48,000
Access the Kubecost dashboard.
kubectl port-forward dash n monitoring svc/kubecost-cost-analyzer 9090:9090

19
04:27:48,000 --> 04:27:54,000
Open localhost 9090.
Three key cost reports to review.

20
04:27:54,000 --> 04:28:00,000
Namespace costs. financial-rag versus monitoring versus kube-system.
Component costs. API pod hours versus agent pod hours versus pgvector storage.

21
04:28:00,000 --> 04:28:06,000
Efficiency. requested versus used CPU and memory.
This gives you right-sizing signals.

22
04:28:06,000 --> 04:28:12,000
Our Kubecost installation is complete.
You can now see exactly where your cloud spend is going.


[## [SECTION: Step 11 — VPA (Components #182–185)]]


23
04:28:12,000 --> 04:28:18,000
Now let's install Vertical Pod Autoscaler or VPA.
VPA watches how much CPU and memory your pods actually use.

24
04:28:18,000 --> 04:28:24,000
Add the Fairwinds Helm repository.
helm repo add fairwinds-stable https://charts.fairwinds.com/stable

25
04:28:24,000 --> 04:28:30,000
Install VPA in the kube-system namespace.
helm upgrade dash dash install vpa fairwinds-stable/vpa dash dash namespace kube-system

26
04:28:30,000 --> 04:28:36,000
Set recommender.enabled to true.
Set updater.enabled to false and admissionPlugin.enabled to false.

27
04:28:36,000 --> 04:28:42,000
Now create the VPA for the API.
We'll put it in infrastructure/vpa/financial-rag-api.yaml

28
04:28:42,000 --> 04:28:48,000
The VPA targets the API Deployment.
updatePolicy updateMode is set to Off.

29
04:28:48,000 --> 04:28:54,000
Why Off mode? VPA in Auto mode restarts pods to apply new resource values.
For an LLM agent mid-reasoning-loop, a restart drops the request.

30
04:28:54,000 --> 04:29:00,000
Use Recommend mode, review weekly, and apply manually during the maintenance window.

31
04:29:00,000 --> 04:29:06,000
MinAllowed is 100 millicpu and 256 megabytes.
MaxAllowed is 4000 millicpu and 8 gigabytes.

32
04:29:06,000 --> 04:29:12,000
Controlled resources are CPU and memory.

33
04:29:12,000 --> 04:29:18,000
Create a similar VPA for the Agent Deployment.
MinAllowed 250 millicpu and 512 megabytes.
MaxAllowed 8000 millicpu and 16 gigabytes.

34
04:29:18,000 --> 04:29:24,000
Apply the VPAs.
kubectl apply -f infrastructure/vpa/financial-rag-api.yaml

35
04:29:24,000 --> 04:29:30,000
Wait 24 hours for VPA to collect data.
Then review recommendations with kubectl describe vpa.

36
04:29:30,000 --> 04:29:36,000
Our VPA configuration is complete.
We now have right-sizing recommendations.


[## [SECTION: Step 12 — Karpenter Consolidation (Components #186–188)]]


37
04:29:36,000 --> 04:29:42,000
Now let's configure Karpenter consolidation policies.
These control how nodes are replaced and consolidated.

38
04:29:42,000 --> 04:29:48,000
The application NodePool uses consolidationPolicy WhenUnderutilized.
consolidateAfter is 30 seconds.

39
04:29:48,000 --> 04:29:54,000
This consolidates quickly when underutilised.
expireAfter is 720 hours, which is 30 days.

40
04:29:54,000 --> 04:30:00,000
Nodes are replaced after 30 days for OS patches.

41
04:30:00,000 --> 04:30:06,000
The ingestion NodePool for spot instances uses consolidationPolicy WhenEmpty.
consolidateAfter is 5 minutes.

42
04:30:06,000 --> 04:30:12,000
Wait 5 minutes after pods exit before terminating the node.
This gives the node time to finish any pending jobs.

43
04:30:12,000 --> 04:30:18,000
The spot-burst NodePool uses consolidationPolicy WhenUnderutilized.
consolidateAfter is 2 minutes.

44
04:30:18,000 --> 04:30:24,000
expireAfter is 24 hours. Short-lived burst nodes expire daily.

45
04:30:24,000 --> 04:30:30,000
Apply the NodePools.
kubectl apply -f infrastructure/helm/karpenter/

46
04:30:30,000 --> 04:30:36,000
Watch consolidation in action.
Scale down replicas, then watch Karpenter logs.

47
04:30:36,000 --> 04:30:42,000
kubectl logs -n karpenter deployment/karpenter --follow pipe grep -i consolidate

48
04:30:42,000 --> 04:30:48,000
Our Karpenter consolidation is complete.
Nodes now scale down efficiently to save cost.


[## [SECTION: Step 13 — Pod Security Admission (Components #191–192)]]


49
04:30:48,000 --> 04:30:54,000
Now let's enable Pod Security Admission.
This is a built-in Kubernetes feature. No extra components to install.

50
04:30:54,000 --> 04:31:00,000
Label the namespace with the restricted Pod Security Standard.
kubectl label namespace financial-rag pod-security.kubernetes.io/enforce=restricted

51
04:31:00,000 --> 04:31:06,000
Also set enforce-version to v1.29.
Set warn and audit to restricted as well.

52
04:31:06,000 --> 04:31:12,000
Now test that privileged pods are rejected.
kubectl run test-privileged with image alpine.

53
04:31:12,000 --> 04:31:18,000
Set securityContext privileged to true.
Expected output shows Error from server Forbidden.

54
04:31:18,000 --> 04:31:24,000
The error says violates PodSecurity restricted.
Privileged containers are now blocked.

55
04:31:24,000 --> 04:31:30,000
Our Pod Security Admission is complete.
The namespace now enforces restricted security standards.


[## [SECTION: Step 14 — OPA Gatekeeper (Components #193–194)]]


56
04:31:30,000 --> 04:31:36,000
Now let's install OPA Gatekeeper.
Gatekeeper is like Pod Security Admission but much more powerful.
You can write any policy you want.

57
04:31:36,000 --> 04:31:42,000
Add the Gatekeeper Helm repository.
helm repo add gatekeeper https://open-policy-agent.github.io/gatekeeper/charts

58
04:31:42,000 --> 04:31:48,000
Install Gatekeeper in the gatekeeper-system namespace.
helm upgrade dash dash install gatekeeper gatekeeper/gatekeeper dash dash namespace gatekeeper-system dash dash create-namespace

59
04:31:48,000 --> 04:31:54,000
Now create a constraint from the k8s_admission.rego policies.
We'll put it in infrastructure/gatekeeper/no-latest-tag.yaml

60
04:31:54,000 --> 04:32:00,000
First, define the ConstraintTemplate.
It wraps the Rego policy for Kubernetes.

61
04:32:00,000 --> 04:32:06,000
The template name is nolatestimage.
The rego code checks if any container image ends with colon latest.

62
04:32:06,000 --> 04:32:12,000
If it does, return a violation message.

63
04:32:12,000 --> 04:32:18,000
Then create the Constraint that applies the template.
kind is NoLatestImage.

64
04:32:18,000 --> 04:32:24,000
The match block applies to the financial-rag namespace.
enforcementAction is set to deny.

65
04:32:24,000 --> 04:32:30,000
Apply the constraint.
kubectl apply -f infrastructure/gatekeeper/no-latest-tag.yaml

66
04:32:30,000 --> 04:32:36,000
Now test that a pod with latest image is rejected.
kubectl run test-latest with image nginx colon latest.

67
04:32:36,000 --> 04:32:42,000
Expected output shows the pod is blocked.
With message that latest tag is not allowed.

68
04:32:42,000 --> 04:32:48,000
Our OPA Gatekeeper is complete.
Kubernetes now enforces no latest tags at admission time.


[## [SECTION: Step 15 — Velero Backup (Components #195–199)]]


69
04:32:48,000 --> 04:32:54,000
Now let's install Velero for backup and restore.
Velero backs up your entire Kubernetes cluster.
Pods, config maps, secrets, and persistent volumes.

70
04:32:54,000 --> 04:33:00,000
Install the Velero CLI first.
brew install velero on macOS.

71
04:33:00,000 --> 04:33:06,000
Install Velero server with S3 backend.
velero install dash dash provider aws dash dash plugins velero/velero-plugin-for-aws

72
04:33:06,000 --> 04:33:12,000
Set bucket to financial-rag-velero-backups.
Set backup-location-config region to us-east-1.

73
04:33:12,000 --> 04:33:18,000
Set snapshot-location-config region to us-east-1.
Provide the secret file with AWS credentials.

74
04:33:18,000 --> 04:33:24,000
Now create the backup schedule.
We'll put it in infrastructure/velero/backup-schedule.yaml

75
04:33:24,000 --> 04:33:30,000
The schedule runs daily at 1 AM UTC.
Why 1 AM? Because the ingestion CronJob runs at 2 AM.

76
04:33:30,000 --> 04:33:36,000
You want the backup before ingestion, not after.
includedNamespaces are financial-rag and vault.

77
04:33:36,000 --> 04:33:42,000
includedResources is star, all resources.
includeClusterResources is true.

78
04:33:42,000 --> 04:33:48,000
TTL is 336 hours, which is 14 days of retention.
snapshotVolumes is true.

79
04:33:48,000 --> 04:33:54,000
labelSelector matches app.kubernetes.io/name equals financial-rag-agent.

80
04:33:54,000 --> 04:34:00,000
Apply the backup schedule.
kubectl apply -f infrastructure/velero/backup-schedule.yaml

81
04:34:00,000 --> 04:34:06,000
Create an on-demand backup before any major upgrade.
velero backup create pre-upgrade-backup dash dash include-namespaces financial-rag dash dash wait

82
04:34:06,000 --> 04:34:12,000
Verify the backup.
velero backup describe pre-upgrade-backup

83
04:34:12,000 --> 04:34:18,000
Test restore to a different namespace.
Never restore directly over production.

84
04:34:18,000 --> 04:34:24,000
velero restore create test-restore dash dash from-backup pre-upgrade-backup
dash dash namespace-mappings financial-rag colon financial-rag-restore dash dash wait

85
04:34:24,000 --> 04:34:30,000
Verify the restore.
kubectl get pods in the financial-rag-restore namespace.

86
04:34:30,000 --> 04:34:36,000
Clean up the test restore.
kubectl delete namespace financial-rag-restore

87
04:34:36,000 --> 04:34:42,000
Our Velero backup is complete.
The cluster now has daily backups and restore capability.


[## [SECTION: Step 16 — Production Readiness Check (Component #203)]]


88
04:34:42,000 --> 04:34:48,000
Now let's create the production readiness check script.
We'll put it in scripts/production-readiness-check.sh

89
04:34:48,000 --> 04:34:54,000
This script validates everything before a major deployment.
It produces a pass or fail report.

90
04:34:54,000 --> 04:35:00,000
First, it checks infrastructure.
Cluster connectivity and all nodes ready.

91
04:35:00,000 --> 04:35:06,000
Next, application pods.
API pods, agent pods, pgvector statefulset, redis statefulset.
All should be running with the correct replica counts.

92
04:35:06,000 --> 04:35:12,000
Next, health endpoints.
API slash health should return status healthy or degraded.

93
04:35:12,000 --> 04:35:18,000
Next, security.
All containers running as non-root. No UID zero.

94
04:35:18,000 --> 04:35:24,000
No latest image tags in production.
Vault agent sidecars running.

95
04:35:24,000 --> 04:35:30,000
Falco running in kube-system.

96
04:35:30,000 --> 04:35:36,000
Next, autoscaling.
HPA for API and agent should be able to scale.

97
04:35:36,000 --> 04:35:42,000
Next, observability.
Prometheus running, Grafana running, OTel Collector running.

98
04:35:42,000 --> 04:35:48,000
Next, backup.
Latest Velero backup should be Completed.

99
04:35:48,000 --> 04:35:54,000
Each check prints a green checkmark, a red X, or a yellow warning.
At the end, it prints passed, failed, and warning counts.

100
04:35:54,000 --> 04:36:00,000
If any failures exist, the script exits with code 1.
Your CI pipeline can block deployment until issues are fixed.

101
04:36:00,000 --> 04:36:06,000
Make the script executable.
chmod plus x scripts/production-readiness-check.sh

102
04:36:06,000 --> 04:36:12,000
Run the check.
./scripts/production-readiness-check.sh financial-rag

103
04:36:12,000 --> 04:36:18,000
Our production readiness check is complete.
Every deployment can now be validated before rollout.


[## [SECTION: Step 17 — FinOps Dashboard (Component #200)]]


104
04:36:18,000 --> 04:36:24,000
Now let's create the FinOps dashboard.
We'll put it in observability/grafana/finops-dashboard.json

105
04:36:24,000 --> 04:36:30,000
The dashboard has four panels.

